{"title_page": "Guy Opperman", "text_new": "{{short description|British politician}}\n<!-- PLEASE USE A SUITABLE TEMPLATE TO FORMAT ANY CITATIONS. BARE URLs ARE LESS TIDY AND LESS INFORMATIVE THAN FULLY FORMATTED CITATIONS. -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Guy Opperman\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Guy Opperman crop 2.jpg\n| caption =\n| office = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister for Pensions and Financial Inclusion]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 14 June 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Richard Harrington (politician)|Richard Harrington]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 17 July 2016\n| term_end1 = 14 June 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[John Penrose]]\n| successor1 = [[Heather Wheeler]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]]\n| term_start2 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = [[Peter Atkinson (politician)|Peter Atkinson]]\n| successor2 = \n| majority2 = 10,549 (22.9%)\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1965|05|18|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/41334.stm |title=Guy Opperman MP |publisher=[[BBC Online]] |work=Democracy Live |date= |accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]], England<ref name=\"ukwhoswho.com\">{{citation |chapter-url= http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251456/ |chapter=Guy Opperman |title=Who's Who |publisher=[[A & C Black]] |accessdate= |chapter-url-access=subscription |title-link=Who's Who (UK) }}</ref>\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Buckingham]] <br /> [[Universit\u00e9 Lille Nord de France|University of Lille]]\n| website = {{url|http://www.guyopperman.co.uk/|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Guy Thomas Opperman'''<ref name=\"ukwhoswho.com\"/> (born 18 May 1965) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, who was first elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]].<ref name=\"Election 2010\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hexhamcourant.co.uk/news/opperman-wins-for-tories-1.705670?referrerPath=/1.257779 |title=Election 2010: Hexham Results |newspaper=[[Hexham Courant]] |publisher=CN Group |accessdate=7 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229231345/http://www.hexhamcourant.co.uk/news/opperman-wins-for-tories-1.705670?referrerPath=%2F1.257779 |archivedate=29 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nOpperman was born in [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]] and was educated at [[Harrow School]], an independent all-boys boarding school. Opperman has a degree in law from the [[University of Buckingham]] and a first-class diploma from the [[Universit\u00e9 Lille Nord de France|University of Lille]], in [[France]].<ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web |url= http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Opperman_Guy.aspx |title=Guy Opperman |work=Conservative Party Profile |publisher=[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] |accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n \nOpperman was [[called to the bar]] in 1989. He spent 20 years as a barrister of which 15 years were spent predominantly at the criminal bar. Opperman prosecuted and defended in a number of murder and rape trials.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n \nWhile a barrister, he did many years of ''[[pro bono]]'' work with the Western Circuit Free Representation Unit and the Bar Pro Bono Unit, providing free legal assistance in hundreds of cases on behalf of [[Victim Support]] and [[Citizens Advice Bureau]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} ''[[The Times]]'' named him \"Lawyer of the Week\" in 2007 and was awarded the Bar Pro Bono Award by the Attorney General, [[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|Lord Goldsmith]] QC, for his voluntary work on behalf of victims in Criminal Injuries Compensation Appeals.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} In 2009, the Attorney General, [[Patricia Scotland|Baroness Scotland]] QC, presented him with a Pro Bono Hero award in the House of Commons for his work on preventing hospital closures.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} He is now a \"door tenant\" at 3PB and is no longer in active practice at the Bar having committed to being a full-time Member of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.3paper.co.uk/profile/guy-opperman |title=Guy Opperman |work=Members |publisher=3PB Barristers |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131020927/http://www.3paper.co.uk/profile/guy-opperman# |archive-date=31 January 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOpperman previously stood for election to Parliament in [[Swindon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Swindon North]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] and for [[Caernarfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Caernarfon]] in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. He was a Councillor in [[Kennet (district)|Kennet]] from 1995 to 1999.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Hexham/Guy+Opperman |title=Guy Opperman |location=London |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511194717/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Hexham/Guy+Opperman |archivedate=11 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOpperman led a legal campaign to oppose the closure of the [[National Health Service|NHS]]'s Savernake Hospital at Marlborough which he credited with saving his mother's life from cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2008/880.html|title=The Queen on the application of Val Compton v Wiltshire Primary Care Trust|work=England and Wales High Court (Administrative Court) Decisions|publisher=[[British and Irish Legal Information Institute|BAILII]]|date=22 April 2008|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career ==\nOpperman was elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]] in Northumberland. He was one of the first MPs in the United Kingdom to employ an apprentice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2012/02/09/jade-the-mp-s-apprentice-steps-up-the-career-ladder-61634-30295211|title=Prudhoe teenager Jade gets apprenticeship with MP|newspaper=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=9 February 2012|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Opperman coordinated the collection of more than 300 toys for disadvantaged children in north east England as part of the Northumberland Conservatives' Christmas appeal, \"Buy One More Toy\".{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn September 2012 Opperman was appointed as [[Private Parliamentary Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Mark Harper]], the Immigration Minister at the [[Home Office]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2012-09-12/full-list-of-conservative-parliamentary-aides|title=Full list of Conservative ministerial aides revealed|publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]|date=12 September 2012|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOpperman has previously described himself as \"rather on the left\" of the Conservative Party and has previously opposed regional pay but supported the [[Living Wage]], regional banks, and industrial activism. He called for his party to do more to show it supports \"the hard working people in our public sector\". In 2012, the ''[[New Statesman]]'' magazine summarised his positions on low wages, corporate responsibility, and apprenticeships in an article called \"Meet the Tories the left should be frightened of\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/politics/2012/10/meet-tories-left-should-be-frightened|last=Davis|first=Rowenna|title=Meet the Tories the left should be frightened of|publisher=[[New Statesman]] |date=9 October 2012|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2013, Opperman declared his support for the Living Wage in an article for the ''New Statesman''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/08/guy-opperman-conservative-case-living-wage|last=Opperman|first=Guy|title=Guy Opperman: the Conservative case for a living wage|publisher=[[New Statesman]]|date=13 August 2013|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> In this article he asked: \"How and why did we let it become acceptable for a full-time job not to pay enough to live on?\".\n\nHe led a campaign to oppose the closure of Savernake Hospital. Opperman has also overseen multiple NHS service closures in his constituency, for instance, the shutting of the overnight urgent care services at [[Hexham General Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hexham-courant.co.uk/news/Overnight-closure-of-hospital-urgent-care-service-likely-to-stay-in-force-9b1cc0c6-b34d-4016-9f40-52b6773dc58f-ds|title=Overnight closure of hospital urgent care service likely to stay in force {{!}} Hexham Courant|website=www.hexham-courant.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Opperman was named by the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority|IPSA]] for an outstanding \u00a3161 in expenses due back, this was later revised to \u00a332.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nOpperman was appointed as Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State at the Department for Work and Pensions on 14 June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/guy-opperman|title=Guy Opperman MP|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Footage from 2013 was uncovered showing him stating that he understood what it was like to live on a zero-hours contract because he once worked as a \u00a3250-per-hour barrister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/tory-dwp-minister-zero-hours-contract-guy-opperman-barrister-250-hour-gig-economy-work-pensions-a7793241.html|title=Tory minister says he understands life on zero-hours contracts because he used to be \u00a3250-an-hour barrister|last=Chapman|first=Ben|work=The Independent|date=16 June 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Weeks later, in response to the group Women Against State Pension Inequality, he was quoted as saying that older women who face cuts to their state pension could take up apprenticeships as a route to re-employment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2017/jul/05/women-hit-by-pension-age-change-can-take-up-apprenticeships|title=Minister suggests women hit by pension age change 'take up apprenticeships'|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|work=The Guardian|date=5 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOpperman faced criticism in October 2017 for pulling out of a pensions fringe event at the [[Conservative Party Conference]] in an apparent attempt to avoid a nearby protest staged by [[Women Against State Pension Inequality]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://citywire.co.uk/new-model-adviser/news/pensions-minister-dodges-womens-event-amid-waspi-protests/a1055658|title=Pensions minister dodges women's event amid Waspi protests|last=Gilbert|first=Jack|work=Citywire|date=4 October 2017|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was criticised in the ''[[Financial Times]]'' in September 2017 for being \"clueless\" about the [[Lifetime ISA]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftadviser.com/opinion/2017/09/15/pensions-minister-is-clueless-about-lisa/|title=Pensions minister is clueless about Lisa|last=Hughes|first=Emma Ann|work=FTAdviser|date=15 September 2017|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref> and for following a \"line of pensions ministers with no interest in pensions stretching back to the 1990s\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftadviser.com/opinion/2017/09/27/no-need-to-scare-expat-pensioners/|title=No need to scare expat pensioners|last=Hazell|first=Tony|work=FTAdviser|date=27 September 2017|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt a hustings event for the 2019 election Opperman stated that families who relied on food banks \u201cmust get better at handling money\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/tory-general-election-candidate-claims-17335882|title=Tory general election candidate claims food bank users need to 'get better at handling money|date=29 November 2019|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.hexham-courant.co.uk/news/18064217.poorer-families-using-food-banks-must-handle-money-better/|title=To help ease continuous food bank use \"we must get better at handling money\"|date=29 November 2019|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brain tumour==\nIn April 2011, Opperman was diagnosed with a brain tumour after suffering from headaches whilst at work in Parliament. He was rushed to hospital on the advice of his fellow Conservative MP and doctor, [[Dan Poulter]], and underwent emergency surgery. He recovered fully after several months.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nGuy Opperman has raised almost \u00a310,000 for charity including over \u00a34,000 in 2011 for the National Brain Appeal at the [[National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery]] which he credits with saving his life after suffering from a [[Brain tumor|brain tumour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalbrainappeal.org/guy-opperman-mp/|title=Guy Opperman MP|date=|publisher=The National Brain Appeal|work=Our Heroes|accessdate=}}</ref> He and Labour MP [[Paul Blomfield]], who also had a brain tumour in 2011,  walked the first section of the [[Pennine Way]] in 2012 to raise money for [[Headway UK]]. In 2012, Opperman walked 280 miles from Sheffield to Scotland raising \u00a32,500 for the Great North Air Ambulance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justgiving.com/GuyGNAA|title=Guy's Page|date=27 July 2012|publisher=Just Giving|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOpperman was a director of his family engineering business until 2009.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} On 2 June 2017, during his general election campaign, Guy married his partner Flora.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/would-hexham-mp-swaps-honeymoon-13144758|title=Would-be MP swaps honeymoon for the campaign trail after wedding clash|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=6 June 2017|work=nechronicle|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOpperman is an amateur jockey and rode his first winner in 1985. He continues to ride and has won a number of [[Point-to-point (steeplechase)|point-to-point]] horse races, including at Downhills, [[Corbridge]] just after his selection as the Conservative Party Candidate for Hexham in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guyopperman.blogspot.co.uk/2009/03/tynedale-point-to-point.html|title=Tyndale Point to Point|date=1 March 2009|publisher=[[Blogger (service)|Blogspot]]|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n\n==Author and blogger==\nIn 2010, Opperman's blog was named as in the top 30 of all MPs by ''[[Total Politics]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guyopperman.blogspot.co.uk/2010/09/top-30.html|title=Top 30|date=4 September 2010|publisher=[[Blogger (service)|Blogspot]]|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Opperman had his first book published, ''Doing Time'', an examination of the prison service and offender rehabilitation in the United Kingdom. In it he offers a consideration of re-offending, prisoner training, drug rehabilitation, prison management and payment by results in the prison system.<ref>{{cite book |last=Opperman |first=Guy |title=Doing Time \u2013 Prisons in the 21st Century |location=Surbiton |publisher=Bretwalda Books |isbn=978-1909099036 |url= https://www.amazon.co.uk/Doing-Time-Prisons-Century-ebook/dp/B009OOWQ8W |accessdate=|date=October 2012 }}</ref>\n \nOpperman is a member of the Advisory Board of the [[High Pay Centre]] and has co-authored an essay with [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] MP [[Caroline Lucas]] and [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] General Secretary [[Frances O'Grady]] entitled \"Better Business: Moral Matters\". In the essay he contrasts community-focussed businesses in his Northumberland seat with the lack of responsibility demonstrated by the banking sector.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highpaycentre.org/pubs/better-business-morals-matter-a-collection-of-essays-about-business-ethics |title=Better Business: Morals Matter \u2013 A collection of essays about business ethics |publisher=High Pay Centre |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.guyopperman.co.uk/ Guy Opperman MP] official website\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Opperman_Guy.aspx |title=Guy Opperman |work=Conservative Party Profile |publisher=[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] |accessdate=7 May 2010}}\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.3paper.co.uk/profile/guy-opperman |title=Guy Opperman |work=Members |publisher=3PB Barristers |accessdate=}}\n*[http://www.hexhamconservatives.co.uk/ Hexham Conservative Association]\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=guy-opperman/4142 |hansard= |hansardcurr= |guardian=9160/guy-opperman |publicwhip=Guy_Opperman |theywork=guy_opperman/hexham |record=Guy-Opperman/Hexham/1059 |bbc= 41334.stm |journalisted=}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Atkinson (politician)|Peter Atkinson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for  [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{North East Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Opperman, Guy}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Buckingham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English bloggers]]\n[[Category:People from Marlborough, Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British politician}}\n<!-- PLEASE USE A SUITABLE TEMPLATE TO FORMAT ANY CITATIONS. BARE URLs ARE LESS TIDY AND LESS INFORMATIVE THAN FULLY FORMATTED CITATIONS. -->\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Guy Opperman\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Guy Opperman crop 2.jpg\n| caption =\n| office = [[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister for Pensions and Financial Inclusion]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start = 14 June 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Richard Harrington (politician)|Richard Harrington]]\n| successor = \n| office1 = [[Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start1 = 17 July 2016\n| term_end1 = 14 June 2017\n| predecessor1 = [[John Penrose]]\n| successor1 = [[Heather Wheeler]]\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]]\n| term_start2 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = [[Peter Atkinson (politician)|Peter Atkinson]]\n| successor2 = \n| majority2 = 10,549 (22.9%)\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1965|05|18|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/41334.stm |title=Guy Opperman MP |publisher=[[BBC Online]] |work=Democracy Live |date= |accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]], England<ref name=\"ukwhoswho.com\">{{citation |chapter-url= http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U251456/ |chapter=Guy Opperman |title=Who's Who |publisher=[[A & C Black]] |accessdate= |chapter-url-access=subscription |title-link=Who's Who (UK) }}</ref>\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Buckingham]] <br /> [[Universit\u00e9 Lille Nord de France|University of Lille]]\n| website = {{url|http://www.guyopperman.co.uk/|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Guy Thomas Opperman'''<ref name=\"ukwhoswho.com\"/> (born 18 May 1965) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician, who was first elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]].<ref name=\"Election 2010\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hexhamcourant.co.uk/news/opperman-wins-for-tories-1.705670?referrerPath=/1.257779 |title=Election 2010: Hexham Results |newspaper=[[Hexham Courant]] |publisher=CN Group |accessdate=7 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229231345/http://www.hexhamcourant.co.uk/news/opperman-wins-for-tories-1.705670?referrerPath=%2F1.257779 |archivedate=29 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nOpperman was born in [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]] and was educated at [[Harrow School]], an independent all-boys boarding school. Opperman has a degree in law from the [[University of Buckingham]] and a first-class diploma from the [[Universit\u00e9 Lille Nord de France|University of Lille]], in [[France]].<ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web |url= http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Opperman_Guy.aspx |title=Guy Opperman |work=Conservative Party Profile |publisher=[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] |accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n \nOpperman was [[called to the bar]] in 1989. He spent 20 years as a barrister of which 15 years were spent predominantly at the criminal bar. Opperman prosecuted and defended in a number of murder and rape trials.{{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n \nWhile a barrister, he did many years of ''[[pro bono]]'' work with the Western Circuit Free Representation Unit and the Bar Pro Bono Unit, providing free legal assistance in hundreds of cases on behalf of [[Victim Support]] and [[Citizens Advice Bureau]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} ''[[The Times]]'' named him \"Lawyer of the Week\" in 2007 and was awarded the Bar Pro Bono Award by the Attorney General, [[Peter Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith|Lord Goldsmith]] QC, for his voluntary work on behalf of victims in Criminal Injuries Compensation Appeals.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} In 2009, the Attorney General, [[Patricia Scotland|Baroness Scotland]] QC, presented him with a Pro Bono Hero award in the House of Commons for his work on preventing hospital closures.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} He is now a \"door tenant\" at 3PB and is no longer in active practice at the Bar having committed to being a full-time Member of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.3paper.co.uk/profile/guy-opperman |title=Guy Opperman |work=Members |publisher=3PB Barristers |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131020927/http://www.3paper.co.uk/profile/guy-opperman# |archive-date=31 January 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOpperman previously stood for election to Parliament in [[Swindon North (UK Parliament constituency)|Swindon North]] at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] and for [[Caernarfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Caernarfon]] in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. He was a Councillor in [[Kennet (district)|Kennet]] from 1995 to 1999.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Hexham/Guy+Opperman |title=Guy Opperman |location=London |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511194717/http://ukpolitics.telegraph.co.uk/Hexham/Guy+Opperman |archivedate=11 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOpperman led a legal campaign to oppose the closure of the [[National Health Service|NHS]]'s Savernake Hospital at Marlborough which he credited with saving his mother's life from cancer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/ew/cases/EWHC/Admin/2008/880.html|title=The Queen on the application of Val Compton v Wiltshire Primary Care Trust|work=England and Wales High Court (Administrative Court) Decisions|publisher=[[British and Irish Legal Information Institute|BAILII]]|date=22 April 2008|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career ==\nOpperman was elected at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]] in Northumberland. He was one of the first MPs in the United Kingdom to employ an apprentice.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.journallive.co.uk/north-east-news/todays-news/2012/02/09/jade-the-mp-s-apprentice-steps-up-the-career-ladder-61634-30295211|title=Prudhoe teenager Jade gets apprenticeship with MP|newspaper=[[The Journal (newspaper)|The Journal]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|date=9 February 2012|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Opperman coordinated the collection of more than 300 toys for disadvantaged children in north east England as part of the Northumberland Conservatives' Christmas appeal, \"Buy One More Toy\".{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn September 2012 Opperman was appointed as [[Private Parliamentary Secretary]] (PPS) to [[Mark Harper]], the Immigration Minister at the [[Home Office]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2012-09-12/full-list-of-conservative-parliamentary-aides|title=Full list of Conservative ministerial aides revealed|publisher=[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]|date=12 September 2012|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOpperman has previously described himself as \"rather on the left\" of the Conservative Party and has previously opposed regional pay but supported the [[Living Wage]], regional banks, and industrial activism. He called for his party to do more to show it supports \"the hard working people in our public sector\". In 2012, the ''[[New Statesman]]'' magazine summarised his positions on low wages, corporate responsibility, and apprenticeships in an article called \"Meet the Tories the left should be frightened of\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/politics/2012/10/meet-tories-left-should-be-frightened|last=Davis|first=Rowenna|title=Meet the Tories the left should be frightened of|publisher=[[New Statesman]] |date=9 October 2012|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2013, Opperman declared his support for the Living Wage in an article for the ''New Statesman''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2013/08/guy-opperman-conservative-case-living-wage|last=Opperman|first=Guy|title=Guy Opperman: the Conservative case for a living wage|publisher=[[New Statesman]]|date=13 August 2013|accessdate=8 May 2015}}</ref> In this article he asked: \"How and why did we let it become acceptable for a full-time job not to pay enough to live on?\".\n\nHe led a campaign to oppose the closure of Savernake Hospital. Opperman has also overseen multiple NHS service closures in his constituency, for instance, the shutting of the overnight urgent care services at [[Hexham General Hospital]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hexham-courant.co.uk/news/Overnight-closure-of-hospital-urgent-care-service-likely-to-stay-in-force-9b1cc0c6-b34d-4016-9f40-52b6773dc58f-ds|title=Overnight closure of hospital urgent care service likely to stay in force {{!}} Hexham Courant|website=www.hexham-courant.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-12-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Opperman was named by the [[Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority|IPSA]] for an outstanding \u00a3161 in expenses due back, this was later revised to \u00a332.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nOpperman was appointed as Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State at the Department for Work and Pensions on 14 June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/guy-opperman|title=Guy Opperman MP|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Footage from 2013 was uncovered showing him stating that he understood what it was like to live on a zero-hours contract because he once worked as a \u00a3250-per-hour barrister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/tory-dwp-minister-zero-hours-contract-guy-opperman-barrister-250-hour-gig-economy-work-pensions-a7793241.html|title=Tory minister says he understands life on zero-hours contracts because he used to be \u00a3250-an-hour barrister|last=Chapman|first=Ben|work=The Independent|date=16 June 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref> Weeks later, in response to the group Women Against State Pension Inequality, he was quoted as saying that older women who face cuts to their state pension could take up apprenticeships as a route to re-employment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2017/jul/05/women-hit-by-pension-age-change-can-take-up-apprenticeships|title=Minister suggests women hit by pension age change 'take up apprenticeships'|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|work=The Guardian|date=5 July 2017|accessdate=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nOpperman faced criticism in October 2017 for pulling out of a pensions fringe event at the [[Conservative Party Conference]] in an apparent attempt to avoid a nearby protest staged by [[Women Against State Pension Inequality]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://citywire.co.uk/new-model-adviser/news/pensions-minister-dodges-womens-event-amid-waspi-protests/a1055658|title=Pensions minister dodges women's event amid Waspi protests|last=Gilbert|first=Jack|work=Citywire|date=4 October 2017|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe was criticised in the ''[[Financial Times]]'' in September 2017 for being \"clueless\" about the [[Lifetime ISA]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftadviser.com/opinion/2017/09/15/pensions-minister-is-clueless-about-lisa/|title=Pensions minister is clueless about Lisa|last=Hughes|first=Emma Ann|work=FTAdviser|date=15 September 2017|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref> and for following a \"line of pensions ministers with no interest in pensions stretching back to the 1990s\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ftadviser.com/opinion/2017/09/27/no-need-to-scare-expat-pensioners/|title=No need to scare expat pensioners|last=Hazell|first=Tony|work=FTAdviser|date=27 September 2017|accessdate=28 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt a hustings event for the 2019 election Opperman stated that families who relied on food banks \u201cmust get better at handling money\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/tory-general-election-candidate-claims-17335882|title=Tory general election candidate claims food bank users need to 'get better at handling money|date=29 November 2019|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url= https://www.hexham-courant.co.uk/news/18064217.poorer-families-using-food-banks-must-handle-money-better/|title=To help ease continuous food bank use \"we must get better at handling money\"|date=29 November 2019|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Brain tumour==\nIn April 2011, Opperman was diagnosed with a brain tumour after suffering from headaches whilst at work in Parliament. He was rushed to hospital on the advice of his fellow Conservative MP and doctor, [[Dan Poulter]], and underwent emergency surgery. He recovered fully after several months.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nGuy Opperman has raised almost \u00a310,000 for charity including over \u00a34,000 in 2011 for the National Brain Appeal at the [[National Hospital for Neurology and Neurosurgery]] which he credits with saving his life after suffering from a [[Brain tumor|brain tumour]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalbrainappeal.org/guy-opperman-mp/|title=Guy Opperman MP|date=|publisher=The National Brain Appeal|work=Our Heroes|accessdate=}}</ref> He and Labour MP [[Paul Blomfield]], who also had a brain tumour in 2011,  walked the first section of the [[Pennine Way]] in 2012 to raise money for [[Headway UK]]. In 2012, Opperman walked 280 miles from Sheffield to Scotland raising \u00a32,500 for the Great North Air Ambulance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justgiving.com/GuyGNAA|title=Guy's Page|date=27 July 2012|publisher=Just Giving|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nOpperman was a director of his family engineering business until 2009.{{citation needed|date=August 2013}} Opperman is a supporter of [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough Football Club]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.express.co.uk/pictures/sport/10425/famous-celebrity-fans-Premier-League-clubs-sportgalleries/Middlesbrough-celebrity-fans-205915|title=Middlesbrough celebrity fans {{!}} Famous celebrity football fans of Premier League clubs {{!}} Sport Galleries {{!}} Pics {{!}} Express.co.uk|work=Express.co.uk|access-date=10 June 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/famous-faces-backing-boros-survival-3718943|title=Famous faces are backing Boro's survival push|last=Passant|first=Andy|date=12 March 2009|work=gazettelive|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref> On 2 June 2017, during his general election campaign, Guy married his partner Flora.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/north-east-news/would-hexham-mp-swaps-honeymoon-13144758|title=Would-be MP swaps honeymoon for the campaign trail after wedding clash|last=Walker|first=Jonathan|date=6 June 2017|work=nechronicle|access-date=10 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOpperman is an amateur jockey and rode his first winner in 1985. He continues to ride and has won a number of [[Point-to-point (steeplechase)|point-to-point]] horse races, including at Downhills, [[Corbridge]] just after his selection as the Conservative Party Candidate for Hexham in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guyopperman.blogspot.co.uk/2009/03/tynedale-point-to-point.html|title=Tyndale Point to Point|date=1 March 2009|publisher=[[Blogger (service)|Blogspot]]|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Author and blogger==\nIn 2010, Opperman's blog was named as in the top 30 of all MPs by ''[[Total Politics]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://guyopperman.blogspot.co.uk/2010/09/top-30.html|title=Top 30|date=4 September 2010|publisher=[[Blogger (service)|Blogspot]]|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, Opperman had his first book published, ''Doing Time'', an examination of the prison service and offender rehabilitation in the United Kingdom. In it he offers a consideration of re-offending, prisoner training, drug rehabilitation, prison management and payment by results in the prison system.<ref>{{cite book |last=Opperman |first=Guy |title=Doing Time \u2013 Prisons in the 21st Century |location=Surbiton |publisher=Bretwalda Books |isbn=978-1909099036 |url= https://www.amazon.co.uk/Doing-Time-Prisons-Century-ebook/dp/B009OOWQ8W |accessdate=|date=October 2012 }}</ref>\n \nOpperman is a member of the Advisory Board of the [[High Pay Centre]] and has co-authored an essay with [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] MP [[Caroline Lucas]] and [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] General Secretary [[Frances O'Grady]] entitled \"Better Business: Moral Matters\". In the essay he contrasts community-focussed businesses in his Northumberland seat with the lack of responsibility demonstrated by the banking sector.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.highpaycentre.org/pubs/better-business-morals-matter-a-collection-of-essays-about-business-ethics |title=Better Business: Morals Matter \u2013 A collection of essays about business ethics |publisher=High Pay Centre |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.guyopperman.co.uk/ Guy Opperman MP] official website\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Opperman_Guy.aspx |title=Guy Opperman |work=Conservative Party Profile |publisher=[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] |accessdate=7 May 2010}}\n*{{cite web |url= http://www.3paper.co.uk/profile/guy-opperman |title=Guy Opperman |work=Members |publisher=3PB Barristers |accessdate=}}\n*[http://www.hexhamconservatives.co.uk/ Hexham Conservative Association]\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=guy-opperman/4142 |hansard= |hansardcurr= |guardian=9160/guy-opperman |publicwhip=Guy_Opperman |theywork=guy_opperman/hexham |record=Guy-Opperman/Hexham/1059 |bbc= 41334.stm |journalisted=}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Atkinson (politician)|Peter Atkinson]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for  [[Hexham (UK Parliament constituency)|Hexham]]|years=[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{North East Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Opperman, Guy}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harrow School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Buckingham]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English bloggers]]\n[[Category:People from Marlborough, Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "name_user": "G1259015", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guy_Opperman"}
